"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751693","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-18","<p>I am replying to both questions as assessments of the effect of the benefit cap are the responsibility of the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The new, lower, tiered benefit cap was introduced from 7 November 2016. The change reduces the total amount a working-age household can receive in benefits to £20,000 for couples and lone parents (£13,400 for single adults with no children) in Great Britain outside Greater London. Within Greater London the level is £23,000 for couples and lone parents (£15,410 for single adults with no children).</p><p>Evidence from the 2014 evaluation of the cap showed very little, if any, impact on homelessness as a direct result of the cap. In the cases of a small numbers of capped households who had been evicted, the Local Authorities noted that they had other reasons for rent arrears and they also failed to engage with relevant services, they were considered intentionally homeless.</p><p> </p><p>The lower cap is still the equivalent of gross family earnings of £25k, and £29k in London. There are a number of exemptions, for example, for people receiving disability payments or people who work and qualify for Working Tax Credits. Discretionary Housing Payments can be made by local authorities to help people adjust to the benefit cap and those payments can be made to prevent people becoming homeless.</p><p> </p><p>To help Local Authorities protect the most vulnerable and to support households adjusting to the reforms, the Government has provided around £900 million funding for the Discretionary Housing Payments scheme since 2011.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","4987","2017-07-18T14:29:25.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751693/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751693/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751693/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-13","Social Security Benefits: Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect of the reduction in the benefit cap in November 2016 on the level of homelessness since that date.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","4986"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751694","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-13","<p>My department commissions research on an ad-hoc basis. This research is often to inform internal policy development and so will not always be published. We keep the publication of such research under review.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-09-13T13:21:53.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751694/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751694/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751694/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","Department for Communities and Local Government: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which research reports his Department commissioned from external bodies between December 2014 and June 2017 have not been published; when each such report was commissioned; what the nature of the research commissioned for each such report was; from whom each such research report was commissioned; what the value of each such commission was; on what date each such report was received by his Department; for what reason each such report has not yet been published; and when he plans to publish each such report.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","4912"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751695","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-20","<p>The numbers of families with children living in temporary accommodation in England can be found in live table 775 published here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-homelessness#statutory-homelessness-and-prevention-and-relief-live-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-homelessness#statutory-homelessness-and-prevention-and-relief-live-tables</a></p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-20T14:12:16.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751695/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751695/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751695/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","Temporary Accommodation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of families with children living in temporary accommodation.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","4913"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751696","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-20","<p>The numbers of families with children living in temporary accommodation in England can be found in live table 775 published here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/621559/Statutory_Homelessness_and_Prevention_and_Relief_Live_Tables_2017_Q1.xls" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/621559/Statutory_Homelessness_and_Prevention_and_Relief_Live_Tables_2017_Q1.xls</a></p><p>Breakdowns by local authority can be found in the detailed LA tables:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-homelessness" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-homelessness</a></p><p>We do not publish data at the regional level.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-20T13:54:44.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751696/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751696/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751696/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","Temporary Accommodation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of families with children living in temporary accommodation in (a) the East Midlands, (b) the North East, (c) the North West, (d) the South East, (e) the South West, (f) the West Midlands, (g) Yorkshire and the Humber and (h) the East of England.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","4914"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751697","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-20","<p>The immediate priority following the Grenfell Tower fire was to identify what type of Aluminium Composite Material cladding was being used, and on how many buildings. Based on that evidence, the decision to undertake whole-system tests of cladding has been taken in response to advice from the expert panel advising the Government on fire safety.</p><p>On 6 July we published details of further tests to be carried out as the next step in helping landlords to ensure the safety of their buildings. These large scale tests will help establish how different types of ACM panels in combination with different types of insulation behave in a fire. Further detail about the next testing stage can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/expert-panel-recommends-further-tests-on-cladding-and-insulation" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/expert-panel-recommends-further-tests-on-cladding-and-insulation</a></p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-20T14:49:13.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751697/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751697/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751697/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, for what reasons whole-system tests of cladding were not undertaken alongside testing samples of cladding material after the Grenfell Tower fire.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","4915"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751698","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-20","<p>Translation services are provided by the local authorities that manage the Westway Assistance Centre using existing contracted providers, with additional support available from voluntary sector organisations.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-20T14:34:39.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751698/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751698/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751698/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps he is taking to ensure that all those homes affected by the Grenfell Tower fire have access to appropriate translation services and that all information provided by the Government and Kensington and Chelsea Council is translated into the 21 languages spoken by the residents of that building.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","4992"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751699","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-20","<p>The Government currently has no plans to introduce restrictions on overseas ownership of new homes on London or elsewhere in the country.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-20T14:30:29.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751699/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751699/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751699/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","Housing: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make an assessment of the potential merits of introducing measures to ensure homes in new London developments are made available to people resident in London before buyers from overseas.","false","Biography information for Vicky Foxcroft","Lewisham, Deptford","Vicky Foxcroft","4917"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751700","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-20","<p>It is the landlord’s responsibility to ensure that people are safe, and cost considerations should not get in the way of this. Where work is necessary to ensure the fire safety of social housing, we will ensure that lack of financial resources will not prevent it going ahead.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-20T15:28:01.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751700/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751700/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751700/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751700/answer/previousversion/5629","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","Council Housing: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what criteria will be used to access whether local authorities are able to afford the refurbishment costs associated with ensuring that their properties are safe.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","4988"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751701","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-18","<p>During the current parliamentary session the department issued 76 holding replies to Named Day written questions from Members of Parliament. When it is not possible to provide a substantive reply to a Named Day written question on the date chosen by the Member, a holding reply is provided to the Member pending a substantive response.</p><p>The department endeavours to respond to all Named Day written questions on the date chosen by the Member but this is not always possible in the timescale available, especially when a question is of a complex nature and requires careful consideration or, in the case of the Grenfell Tower fire, where the situation is evolving at pace, and it is essential we provide accurate information.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-18T15:50:58.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751701/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751701/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751701/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","Department for Communities and Local Government: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, on how many occasions his Department has answered that it will not be possible to answer a parliamentary written question within the usual time period in the 2017-19 session.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","4989"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751702","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-18","<p>As part of the Local Government Finance Settlement, central grant allocations for both stand alone and combined fire authorities for 2018-19 and 2019-20 can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/593187/Supporting_table_Key_information_for_local_authorities.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/593187/Supporting_table_Key_information_for_local_authorities.xlsx</a></p><p>Grant allocations beyond 2019-20 will be subject to a future spending review.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-18T15:51:39.843Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751702/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751702/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751702/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","Fire and Rescue Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will publish allocations as part of the Local Government Settlement for the central grant for metropolitan and combined fire authorities in England over the next five years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","4990"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751703","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-20","<p>My Department has not undertaken an estimate of the potential financial effect on police forces of the recent business rates revaluation, nor have we had any discussions with representatives of police forces on this matter. The revaluation was fiscally neutral with the majority of ratepayers seeing no increase or a reduction in their bills. We have put in place a £3.6 billion transitional relief scheme for England to support the minority of ratepayers that have received increased bills.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-20T14:08:48.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751703/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751703/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751703/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","Police Stations: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate his Department has made of the potential financial effect on police forces of changes to the level of business rates on local police stations; and what discussions he has had with representatives of police forces on those changes.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","4809"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751704","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-09-06","<p>My officials have had various discussions with a range of local authorities in the West Midlands. The Government has an ambitious programme to bring brownfield land back into use in England, as set out in the Housing White Paper.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-09-06T16:16:40.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751704/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751704/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751704/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751704/answer/previousversion/5621","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","Derelict Land: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what discussions his Department has had with local authorities on the development of brownfield sites for housing in the West Midlands.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","4796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751705","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-20","<p>Following the tragedy at Grenfell Tower, the Prime Minister has committed to look at wider issues. This work will need to be progressed after the publication of the terms of reference for the public inquiry and the guidelines produced by RECONASS will be considered as part of that exercise.</p><p>An independent expert panel has been set up to provide advice to the Government on any immediate measures needed to make buildings safe following the Grenfell Tower fire. The panel will be led by Sir Ken Knight, former London Fire Commissioner and former Government Chief Fire and Rescue Adviser. It will consider safety measures, policies, inspection and regulation, taking account of both the Grenfell Tower fire and ongoing fire safety inspections. It will look at any immediate action required to ensure public confidence that everything possible is being done to make all public and private buildings safe as quickly as possible.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-20T14:37:07.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751705/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751705/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751705/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","Public Buildings: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the potential benefits to fire safety and post fire response in respect of public buildings of the guidelines produced by the EU research project RECONASS.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","4830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751706","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-21","<p>The Department does not hold this information.</p><p>Following the Grenfell Tower fire, the Department has implemented a Building Safety Programme which includes a checking and testing process for tower blocks. This is explained in more detail in its explanatory note of 30 June at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/explanatory-note-on-safety-checks-and-testing" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/explanatory-note-on-safety-checks-and-testing</a></p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-21T11:14:50.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751706/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751706/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751706/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","High Rise Flats: Natural Gas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what information his Department holds on the number of high-rise towers similar to Grenfell Tower that contain gas pipes supplying all floors.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","4825"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751707","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-21","<p>Safety is the primary concern of the smart metering programme. Energy suppliers are responsible for installing smart meters and are required to comply with a number of regulations and other requirements that relate to the safety of installations and appliances. These include the Gas Safety (Installations and Use) Regulations (1998), the Meter Asset Managers’ Code of Practice (MAMCoP) and the Meter Operators Code of Practice Agreement (MOCOPA) which set out the roles, responsibilities and expectations of meter installers when safety issues are identified during meter installation visits. The Government have also put in place additional requirements through the Smart Metering Installation Code of Practice (SMICoP) which require energy suppliers to ensure that installers are appropriately trained.</p><p>Smart metering is also providing an opportunity to detect pre-existing safety issues that would have otherwise taken longer to identify. Gas and Electricity Network Operators have an important role to play in resolving such issues. They are working closely with suppliers to support a safe installation process.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-07-21T12:52:37.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751707/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751707/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751707/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-13","High Rise Flats: Natural Gas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether gas pipes in high-rise blocks similar to Grenfell Tower are routinely checked for safety during the process of installing smart meters.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","4826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751708","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-20","<p>Councils already have the power to ban pavement parking by means of a Traffic Regulation Order (TRO). Following discussions with local authorities and other stakeholders my department is planning to launch a survey in autumn 2017 in order to gather evidence about the TRO procedure, the costs and timescales for processing TROs, and information about options for change.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-20T13:37:34.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751708/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751708/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751708/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-13","Parking: Pedestrian Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to give councils outside London the power to ban pavement parking in order to reduce problems experienced by people with visual impairments.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","4827"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751709","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-25","<p>We wrote on 22 June and 11 July to update all Members of Parliament on the Grenfell Tower disaster and will continue to provide regular updates.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-25T14:54:19.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751709/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751709/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751709/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will provide weekly updates on the number of Grenfell Tower fire survivors who have (a) been rehoused permanently and (b) accepted accommodation throughout the period of Parliamentary recess.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","4836"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751710","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-24","<p>The Department’s view is that external walls in a tower block can meet the Building Regulations requirement for resisting fire spread in two ways. The first is for each individual component of the wall to be of limited combustibility, and to each meet set standards. The second is to ensure that all the combined elements of a wall, when tested as a whole system, have sufficient fire spread resistance to meet a set standard.</p><p>We are currently undertaking further testing of whole external wall systems to determine whether they would have sufficient fire spread resistance. We will release further details when the findings are available.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-24T15:42:29.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751710/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751710/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751710/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many of the cladding samples that failed safety tests were not compliant with building regulations for buildings higher than 18 metres.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","4834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751711","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-20","<p>The definition of spending power has changed over the period 2010-11 to 2019-20, with core spending power being first introduced at the 2016-17 Local Government Finance Settlement. The changes in definition mean that combining these year on year changes to calculate an overall change for the period 2010-11 to 2019-20 is not meaningful. The table below shows the year on year change in spending power over the period 2010-11 to 2019-20:</p><p /><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>2017-18</p></td><td><p>2018-19</p></td><td><p>2019-20</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>South Tyneside</p></td><td><p>-8.8%</p></td><td><p>-5.6%</p></td><td><p>-1.2%</p></td><td><p>-4.6%</p></td><td><p>-3.8%</p></td><td><p>-4.1%</p></td><td><p>2.0%</p></td><td><p>0.3%</p></td><td><p>1.6%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Gateshead</p></td><td><p>-7.3%</p></td><td><p>-3.6%</p></td><td><p>-1.4%</p></td><td><p>-4.3%</p></td><td><p>-3.6%</p></td><td><p>-3.9%</p></td><td><p>1.9%</p></td><td><p>0.7%</p></td><td><p>1.9%</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-20T13:59:59.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751711/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751711/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751711/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","Local Government Finance: Tyne and Wear","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the change in the core spending power of the (a) South Tyneside and (b) Gateshead local authorities has been in each year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","4843"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751712","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-20","<p>Live table 784, published here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-homelessness#homelessness-summary-local-authority-level-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-homelessness#homelessness-summary-local-authority-level-tables</a>, shows the number of statutory homelessness acceptances and numbers of households in temporary accommodation for each local authority in England since 2004/05. These totals are for England, not the UK. Statistics on homelessness are not collected at the level of parliamentary constituencies.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-20T14:06:50.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751712/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751712/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of homeless people in (a) Jarrow constituency, (b) South Tyneside, (c) the North East and (d) the UK in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","4845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751713","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-20","<p>At Budget 2016 the government announced reductions in business rates to benefit all ratepayers – which will cost almost £9 billion over the next 5 years. The government has set an aim to revalue properties more frequently for business rates and will provide an update in due course.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-20T16:47:53.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751713/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751713/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751713/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751713/answer/previousversion/5623","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what progress has been made on reform of business rates.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","4896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751714","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-20","<p>The table below shows the total receipts of national non-domestic rates collected in the financial year, irrespective of the year to which it relates, for Southampton City Council from 2012-13 to 2016-17. This total includes the amount collected in respect of the billing year, in respect of the previous years and an estimate of receipts in respect of the subsequent billing year. These figures are also net of refunds and exclude court and administration costs.</p><p><br>Figures for 2010-11 and 2011-12 were not published at the local authority level.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Total receipts of national non-domestic rates collected irrespective of the year to which it relates in Southampton (£000s)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>98,022</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>100,147</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>103,245</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>102,998</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>103,918</p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Source: QRC4 (Quarterly receipts of council tax and non-domestic rates collection)</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><br>Further details for each year can be found at the following link <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/council-tax-statistics#collection-rates-for-council-tax-and-non-domestic-rates" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/council-tax-statistics#collection-rates-for-council-tax-and-non-domestic-rates</a>. Further local authority level data for 2016-17 can be found at the following link <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/622535/Drop_down.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/622535/Drop_down.xlsx</a></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-20T16:47:08.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751714/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751714/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751714/answer/previousversion/5624","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","Non-domestic Rates: Southampton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much Southampton City Council collected in business rates in each of the last seven years.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","4897"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751715","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-08-07","<p>Ministers in my department visit a variety of projects, and meet with representatives of local authorities, voluntary and charity sector organisations, policy experts and other partners on a regular basis to discuss a range of issues including homelessness.</p><p>The Government publishes a list of all ministerial meetings with external bodies on departmental business on a quarterly basis. This is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dclg-ministerial-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/dclg-ministerial-data</a></p><p /> <p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-08-07T16:32:41.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751715/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751715/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751715/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent meetings he has had with (a) local authority leaders and (b) charity and voluntary sector representatives to discuss homelessness.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","4922"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751716","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-20","<p>The department publishes regular statistics on rough sleeping, statutory homelessness and homelessness prevention and relief. The latest statistics can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/homelessness-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/homelessness-statistics</a>.</p><p>Homelessness charities regularly publish research and information on the homeless population. Ministers in the department visit a variety of projects and regularly meet with key partners to discuss homelessness issues.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-20T14:13:45.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751716/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751716/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751716/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what recent representations he has received on the (a) size and (b) condition of the homeless population.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","4923"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751717","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-20","<p>The information requested is available at the following link, (DCLG budget details are on pages 73 and 74):</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dclg-annual-report-and-accounts-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dclg-annual-report-and-accounts-2016-to-2017</a></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-20T13:51:33.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751717/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751717/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751717/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","Department for Communities and Local Government: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will publish the levels of funding allocated to his Department in each of the next three years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","4881"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751718","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-20","<p>The numbers of households found to be intentionally homeless and in priority need by local authorities in England since 1998 can be found in live table 770 published here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-homelessness#statutory-homelessness-and-prevention-and-relief-live-tables" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-homelessness#statutory-homelessness-and-prevention-and-relief-live-tables</a></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-20T14:51:16.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751718/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751718/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751718/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how many people were classified by local authorities as intentionally homeless in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","4880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751719","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-20","<p>Statistics on vacant dwellings in England and in each local authority district are published in the Department’s live table 615 which is available at the following link. This table shows the annual total numbers of empty homes and those vacant longer than six months and also vacant dwellings in the local authority, housing association and other public sector tenures.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-dwelling-stock-including-vacants" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-dwelling-stock-including-vacants</a></p><p>The number of homes vacant for more than six months is now at its lowest level since records began, with over 116,000 long term empty properties brought back in to use since 2009.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-20T14:33:13.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751719/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751719/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751719/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-07-13","Empty Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number empty dwellings in (a) Bath, (b) Birmingham, (c) Bradford, (d) Brighton and Hove, (e) Bristol, (f) Cambridge, (g) Canterbury, (h) Carlisle, (i) Chester, (j) Chichester, (k) the City of London, (l) Coventry, (m) Derby, (n) Durham, (o) Ely, (p) Exeter, (q) Gloucester, (r) Hereford, (s) Kingston upon Hull, (t) Lancaster, (u) Leeds, (v) Leicester, (w) Lichfield, (x) Lincoln, (y) Liverpool, (z) Manchester, (aa) Newcastle upon Tyne, (bb) Norwich, (cc) Nottingham, (dd) Oxford, (ee) Peterborough, (ff) Plymouth, (gg) Portsmouth, (hh) Preston, (ii) Ripon, (jj) Salford, (kk) Salisbury, (ll