"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751813","Home Office","false","2017-07-18","<p>There is no evidence that the creation of the new offence of working illegally has prevented the identification of and provision of assistance to victims of modern slavery and the prevention of trafficking. The new offence has strengthened the ability of the UK to deal with those who break our immigration laws for economic benefit by working illegally in the country.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-07-18T14:38:44.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751813/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751813/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751813/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-13","Undocumented Workers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect of the creation of the offence of illegal working on her Department's ability to (a) identify and support victims of and (b) prevent trafficking and modern slavery.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","4863"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751814","Home Office","false","2017-07-19","<p>Ministers receive a number of applications throughout the year, which are typically referred to Her Majesty’s Inspectorate of Constabulary to review before a final decision. Special Grant is a discretionary budget and the number of applications that will be received throughout the year is unknown. The Home Office publishes the applications and decisions taken on Special Grant at the end of the financial year. This can be found at the link below. Data relating to 2016/17 will be published shortly.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/police-funding-special-grant-applications" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/police-funding-special-grant-applications</a></p><p> </p><p>Applications for Special Grant from 2007 to 2014 can be found at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/special-grants-paid-to-the-police-forces-in-england-and-wales-from-2007-to-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/special-grants-paid-to-the-police-forces-in-england-and-wales-from-2007-to-2014</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-07-19T12:55:42.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751814/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751814/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751814/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-13","Police: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answer of 13 March 2017 to Question 3658, how many requests for special grants from which police forces HM Inspectorate of Constabulary is considering (a) now and (b) for 2017-18.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","4910"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751815","Home Office","false","2017-07-18","<p>The Government has no plans to introduce drug consumption rooms for those who wish to use intravenous drugs which have been illicitly obtained.</p><p> </p><p>As set out in the 2017 Drug Strategy, published 14 July, recovery from drug misuse is a core part of our balanced approach. Drug treatment is invaluable to individuals, their families and the communities in which they live, and it is vital there is access to a range of options that can be tailored to individual need, to provide the best possible chances of recovery. People using drugs they have bought on the street is not part of a structured treatment plan.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-07-18T14:37:54.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751815/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751815/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751815/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-13","Drugs: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the Government's policy is on safe injecting facilities.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","4852"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751816","Home Office","false","2017-07-19","<p>The decision to procure and deploy body worn video (BWV) cameras is one for Police and Crime Commissioner and chief officers.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-07-19T12:53:47.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751816/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751816/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751816/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-13","Police: Cameras","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps she is taking to ensure that all on-duty uniformed and armed officers wear body-worn cameras.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","4840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751817","Home Office","false","2017-07-21","<p>The UK continues to work with EU partners to tackle modern slavery and already has well-established rights and protections for victims of modern slavery and human trafficking, including through the National Referral Mechanism and the Modern Slavery Act 2015.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-21T11:07:18.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751817/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751817/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751817/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-13","Human Trafficking: EEA Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect of the UK leaving the EU on the prevention of trafficking of EEA nationals.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","4824"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751818","Home Office","false","2017-09-05","<p>The Home Office collects and publishes statistics on the number of police officers employed by each police force in England and Wales. These data are published in the ‘Police workforce, England and Wales’ statistical bulletins, which are available here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/police-workforce-england-and-wales" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/police-workforce-england-and-wales</a></p><p>Data on the number of male and female officers, by police force area, as at 31 March 2016, can be found in Table_H1 of the accompanying data tables here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-workforce-england-and-wales-31-march-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-workforce-england-and-wales-31-march-2016</a></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-09-05T10:23:57.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751818/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751818/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751818/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-13","Police: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many police officers at (a) Lancashire, (b) Greater Manchester, (c) Cumbria, (d) Merseyside and (e) Cheshire Constabulary identify as either (i) male, (ii) female, (iii) gay, (iv) lesbian, (v) bisexual, (vi) transgender, (vii) gender fluid, (viii) bi-gender, (ix) non-binary, (x) gender queer, (xi) gender non-conforming, (xii) tri-gender, (xiii) all genders, (xiv) intersex or (xv) another gender identity.","false","Biography information for Sir Mark Hendrick","Preston","Mr Mark Hendrick","4819"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751819","Home Office","false","2017-07-18","<p>The Government will set out its plans in due course for redesigning the immigration system to introduce controls on future migration to the UK by EU nationals, including any plans for adjusting statutory checks by employers, landlords and other service providers.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-07-18T14:36:35.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751819/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751819/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751819/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-13","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, pursuant to the Answer of 12 July 2017 to Question 3708, on the period of blanket residence permission outlined in paragraph 24 of her Department's policy paper, Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU, published on 26 June 2017, how (a) employers, (b) landlords, (c) banks and building societies, (d) the DVLA and (e) benefit agencies will be able to determine who has deemed leave.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","4802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751820","Home Office","false","2017-07-18","<p>Decisions on how the police enforce the law and deploy their available resources, including collaboration arrangements, are the responsibility of individual Chief Officers, taking into account the specific local problems and demands with which they are faced.</p><p>The Home Office has therefore not made any assessment of the effect of the withdrawal of West Mercia Police from the Central Motorway Police Group (CMPG) on levels of public safety.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","4773","2017-07-18T12:45:06.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751820/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751820/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751820/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-13","Central Motoring Police Group","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect of the withdrawal of West Mercia Police from the Central Motorway Police Group on levels of public safety; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","4774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751821","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-20","<p>The Department contributes to reducing the impacts of illegal, unreported and unregulated fishing through two multilateral programmes.</p><p>DFID core funding to the UN Food and Agriculture Organisation includes support to the activities of its Fisheries and Aquaculture Department and the International Plan of Action to Prevent, Deter, and Eliminate Illegal, Unreported and Unregulated Fishing. UK support to the Global Environment Facility helps strengthen the management of fisheries and marine protected areas.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-07-20T16:46:55.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751821/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751821/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751821/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-13","Developing Countries: Fisheries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many projects her Department is currently supporting are aimed specifically at reducing the impacts of illegal, unreported and unregulated fishing.","false","Biography information for Mrs Pauline Latham","Mid Derbyshire","Pauline Latham","4813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751822","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-20","<p>The Department supports activities aimed at achieving Sustainable Development Goal 14 through our funding to the UN Food and Agriculture Organisation (FAO) and the Global Environment Facility (GEF). For example FAO hosts the International Plan of Action to Prevent, Deter, and Eliminate Illegal, Unreported and Unregulated Fishing. The GEF has funded marine protected areas across the world that are more than twice the size of Alaska.</p><p>The UK’s core support to FAO in Financial Year 2016-17 was £17,681,203. DFID’s contribution to the Global Environment Facility in Financial Year 2016017 was £52,500,000. Neither FAO nor the GEF publish a breakdown of spending specifically on SDG14.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-07-20T16:47:53.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751822/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751822/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751822/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-13","Sustainable Development: Marine Environment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much funding is currently allocated by her Department to projects aimed at achieving Sustainable Development Goal 14.","false","Biography information for Mrs Pauline Latham","Mid Derbyshire","Pauline Latham","4814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751823","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-18","<p>The Department for International Development (DfID) provides funding to the International Citizen Service (ICS) programme to enable young people from across Britain and developing countries to take part in international volunteering.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1 provides an outline of DfID expenditure on ICS in each of the last five financial years.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p><strong>Table – ICS Expenditure</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Financial year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Expenditure</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>7,399,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>16,927,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>24,443,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>26,263,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>25,166,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-07-18T16:07:38.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751823/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751823/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751823/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-13","International Citizen Service: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how much statutory funding the International Citizen Service programme has received in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","4980"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751824","Department for International Development","false","2017-07-18","<p>The International Citizen Service (ICS) provides opportunities for young people from across Britain and developing countries to take part in international volunteering.</p><p> </p><p>Table 1 shows how many participants have taken part in ICS in each of the last five years. It also includes the split between British volunteers and those from developing countries.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="4"><p><strong>Table 1 – ICS Participants</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>British volunteers</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Developing country volunteers</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Yearly total</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>501</p></td><td><p>392</p></td><td><p>893</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>2023</p></td><td><p>1354</p></td><td><p>3377</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>2918</p></td><td><p>2693</p></td><td><p>5611</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>3627</p></td><td><p>3532</p></td><td><p>7159</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>3211</p></td><td><p>3206</p></td><td><p>6417</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-07-18T16:10:07.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751824/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751824/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751824/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-07-13","International Citizen Service: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many 18 to 25-year-olds took part in the International Citizens Service programme in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","4979"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751825","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-18","<p>Since 2010 there have been 23 mergers of coroner areas in England and Wales, reducing the overall number from 116 to 92 coroner areas.</p><p> </p><p>It is the Chief Coroner’s aim, which the Government supports, to move, over time, to around 75 coroner areas, each having between 3,000 and 5,000 deaths reported annually. The aimn of this change is to promote consistency and generate efficiencies for local authorities, which fund coroner services.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Justice does not have operational responsibility for the coroner services and does not hold information about the number of coroner’s offices that have closed.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","4847","2017-07-18T17:01:23.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751825/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751825/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751825/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-13","Coroners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many coroner's offices have been closed in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Graham P Jones","Hyndburn","Graham P Jones","4855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751826","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-20","<p>This information requested is not held centrally.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-07-20T15:29:44.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751826/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751826/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751826/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-13","Rape: Trials","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many cases where a rape complainant's previous sexual history was used as evidence in court without an application being made to the judge under subsection 41(3)(c)(i) of the Youth Justice and Criminal Evidence Act 1999 prior to the trial have taken place in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","4856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751827","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-18","<p>Since 2010 there have been 23 mergers of coroner areas in England and Wales, reducing the overall number from 116 to 92 coroner areas.</p><p> </p><p>It is the Chief Coroner’s aim, which the Government supports, to move, over time, to around 75 coroner areas, each having between 3,000 and 5,000 deaths reported annually. The aimn of this change is to promote consistency and generate efficiencies for local authorities, which fund coroner services.</p><p> </p><p>The Ministry of Justice does not have operational responsibility for the coroner services and does not hold information about the number of coroner’s offices that have closed.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","4855","2017-07-18T17:01:22.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751827/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751827/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751827/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-13","Coroners","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many coroner's offices have been subject to mergers in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Graham P Jones","Hyndburn","Graham P Jones","4847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751828","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-18","<p>Our vision is for a modern and world-renowned justice system that is swifter, more accessible and easier to use for everyone. The modernisation programme is now in its second year and is progressing well. Tax Appeal Online was launched in June and a number of new services are being tested with the public. These include Probate Online and online tracking in the Social Security &amp; Child Support Tribunal. In the magistrates’ court, good progress is being made in developing a simpler way of deciding summary, non-imprisonable offences using streamlined processes and a new digital system.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-07-18T16:34:15.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751828/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751828/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751828/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-13","Courts: Reform","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent progress has been made on the court reform programme.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","4937"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751829","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-20","<p>The Government will publish Part 2 of its response in due course.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-07-20T14:42:53.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751829/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751829/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751829/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-13","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when his Department plans to publish Part 2 of its response to the consultation entitled Reforming the soft tissue injury (whiplash) claims process.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","4929"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751830","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-20","<p>The Ministry of Justice has not provided any such guidance to the Children and Family Court Advisory and Support Service (Cafcass).</p><p> </p><p>Cafcass has produced guidance to its social work practitioners on this as part of its Operating Framework on which it is currently consulting.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-07-20T14:26:19.847Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751830/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751830/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751830/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-13","Family Courts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what guidance his Department has issued to the Children and Family Court Advisory and Support Service on interviewing children in family court cases.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","4925"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751831","Prime Minister","false","2017-07-18","<p>A reply has been sent.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-07-18T15:11:43.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751831/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751831/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751831/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-07-13","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, when she plans to reply to the letter, sent via email, from the hon. Member for West Bromwich East, of 12 June 2017, on the appointment of the right hon. Member for Surrey Heath to the Cabinet.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","4974"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751832","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-18","<p>The A595 in this location is a local road and the responsibility of Cumbria County Council.</p><p> </p><p>Later this year the Department for Transport plans to consult on its plans to establish a Major Road Network, which would include the most important local authority A-Roads. A share of the National Road Fund, funded by Vehicle Excise Duty, will be set aside to fund improvements on this Network, which could include roads such as the A595 at Grizebeck.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-18T16:17:49.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751832/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751832/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751832/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-13","A595: Grizebeck","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to open a consultation on improvements to the A595 near Grizebeck before the end of the current parliamentary session.","false","Biography information for John Woodcock","Barrow and Furness","John Woodcock","4944"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751833","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-18","<p>The freedom pass is managed by London Councils and the Department has no involvement in issuing freedom passes or the eligibility criteria. We do not hold statistics on the number of people who hold different types of freedom passes.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-18T10:26:56.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751833/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751833/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751833/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-13","Travel: Concessions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many people with a Disabled Person's Freedom Pass in London are aged between 16 and 64; and how many people in London hold an Older Person's Freedom Pass.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","4857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751834","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-18","<p>Following feedback from public consultation, the design of the new roundabout, known as Pellens Corner, had to be revised.</p><p> </p><p>Highways England recently awarded a contract for the construction of the new roundabout, and survey investigation work commenced on 17 July to enable the design and construction programme to be finalised.</p><p> </p><p>The construction of the new roundabout is expected to commence later this summer.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-18T10:22:24.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751834/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751834/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751834/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-13","A120: Roundabouts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the reasons are for the time taken to commence the construction of the new roundabout at the junction of Harwich Road and the A120 east of Colchester; and when that construction is planned to begin.","false","Biography information for Sir Bernard Jenkin","Harwich and North Essex","Mr Bernard Jenkin","4853"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751835","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-18","<p>The freedom pass is administered by London Councils. The times at which freedom passes may be used, above the statutory minimum, is a matter for the Mayor.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-18T10:32:54.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751835/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751835/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751835/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-13","Travel: Concessions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what plans he has to remove the time limits on the use of the Disabled Person's Freedom Pass.","false","Biography information for Ms Harriet Harman","Camberwell and Peckham","Ms Harriet Harman","4854"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751836","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-18","<p>To date the Government has not targeted any of its support for electric vehicle chargepoints at petrol stations. All Government funded public chargepoints are required to be registered on the Government’s National Chargepoint Registry, an open source data set containing information on the type and geographical location of chargepoints. The registry is available online at: <a href="http://www.national-charge-point-registry.uk/" target="_blank">www.national-charge-point-registry.uk</a>. The Office for Low Emission Vehicles is considering what future support to provide for public charging infrastructure, and will confirm its approach in due course.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-07-18T10:43:52.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751836/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751836/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751836/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-13","Garages and Petrol Stations: Electric Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many petrol stations have received funding from the public purse for installing charging stations for electric vehicles.","false","Biography information for John McNally","Falkirk","John McNally","4781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751837","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-21","<p>The Secretary of State has made no recent assessment of the capacity of Swindon station.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-07-21T09:55:49.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751837/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751837/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751837/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-13","Swindon Station","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the capacity of Swindon rail station.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","4828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751838","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-18","<p>The Government supports the industry and its efforts to find deliverable solutions to this increasingly high profile issue. It is important to ensure that all air passengers have a safe and pleasant experience when flying.</p><p> </p><p>The industry bodies have joined together to create the UK Aviation Industry Code of Practice on Disruptive Passengers, with the purpose of creating a common, consistent approach that co-ordinates and enhances existing efforts to prevent and minimise disruptive passenger behaviour.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will continue to engage and meet with a broad range of operators in the aviation sector to explore any further actions to support the Code.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-07-18T12:54:59.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751838/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751838/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751838/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-13","Aviation: Alcoholic Drinks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to engage with the airline industry on tackling problems caused by alcohol consumption on airplanes.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","4822"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751839","Department of Health","false","2017-07-19","<p>The National Health Service Couch to 5k programme was initially a nine week podcast series which was downloaded more than 1.5 million times. The success of the service led to the development of the Couch to 5k app in partnership with the British Broadcasting Corporation.</p><p> </p><p>Public Health England began leadership of the Couch to 5k programme in 2016, where the mobile phone app was developed. The app has received more than 500,000 downloads since launch<sup>1</sup>. The feedback from users is overwhelmingly positive with many referencing the voice-over from popular coaches being especially motivating.</p><p> </p><p>The app does not record mobile sensor data and there is no historical app data available to compare pre and post usage.</p><p> </p><p><sup>1</sup>Source: Google Analytics</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2017-07-19T13:06:26.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751839/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751839/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751839/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-13","Running","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the NHS Couch to 5K running scheme on improving levels of physical activity.","false","Biography information for Nick Smith","Blaenau Gwent","Nick Smith","4810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751840","Women and Equalities","false","2017-07-18","<p>The Equality and Human Rights Commission is an independent public body and decisions about the roles and responsibilities of its Board members, and how these are communicated within the organisation, are matters for the Commission itself.</p><p>I have therefore asked the Commission’s Chief Executive Officer to write to my hon. Friend with the information requested. I will place a copy of the letter in the libraries of both Houses.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","4777 ; 4778","2017-07-18T16:40:52.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751840/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751840/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751840/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-07-13","Equality and Human Rights Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, whether the decision to abolish the role of disability commissioner was taken outside of a Equality and Human Rights Commission Board meeting; and when that decision was made.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","4776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751841","Women and Equalities","false","2017-07-18","<p>The Equality and Human Rights Commission is an independent public body and decisions about the roles and responsibilities of its Board members, and how these are communicated within the organisation, are matters for the Commission itself.</p><p>I have therefore asked the Commission’s Chief Executive Officer to write to my hon. Friend with the information requested. I will place a copy of the letter in the libraries of both Houses.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","4776 ; 4778","2017-07-18T16:40:52.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751841/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751841/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751841/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-07-13","Equality and Human Rights Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, (a) how and (b) when the decision to abolish the role of disability commissioner was communicated to the Equality and Human Rights Commission's Disability Advisory Committee.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","4777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751842","Women and Equalities","false","2017-07-18","<p>The Equality and Human Rights Commission is an independent public body and decisions about the roles and responsibilities of its Board members, and how these are communicated within the organisation, are matters for the Commission itself.</p><p>I have therefore asked the Commission’s Chief Executive Officer to write to my hon. Friend with the information requested. I will place a copy of the letter in the libraries of both Houses.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","4776 ; 4777","2017-07-18T16:40:52.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751842/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751842/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751842/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2017-07-13","Equality and Human Rights Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, whether the Equality and Human Rights Commission's Disability Advisory Committee was (a) consulted and (b) informed in advance of the abolition of the role of disability commissioner in June 2017.","false","Biography information for Heidi Allen","South Cambridgeshire","Heidi Allen","4778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751843","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-18","<p>As a large employer we understand the potential impact that any closure or relocation of an office may have. This is why we carefully considered the wider impacts on local communities in reviewing our estate. The sites we intend to keep were identified as part of our longer-term strategy.</p><p>The increased use of digital services means that many offices are underutilised; meaning that we are spending money on rent for space that is unused rather than on services and support. Our plans seek to redress that. The department is committed to retaining an accessible jobcentre network and continuing to serve customers in all areas. We are recruiting and expect to have more work coaches in March 2018 compared to today.</p><p>We will work to minimise the need for redundancy wherever we can, and seek to redeploy colleagues into new roles, but before any final decisions about redundancies are made, there will be full consultation with affected colleagues and trade unions.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-18T09:19:23.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751843/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751843/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751843/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-13","Jobcentres: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether he has made an assessment of the effect of jobcentre and Jobcentre Plus closures on levels of employment.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","4821"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751844","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-18","<p>DWP are currently undertaking work, in conjunction with a housing association, to investigate the reality of rent arrears in Universal Credit. It aims to understand the true level of rent arrears for their tenants, what is causing them and any impacts Universal Credit may be having.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-18T09:17:07.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751844/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751844/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751844/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-13","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department has commissioned research into the effect of the roll-out of universal credit on levels of household debt.","false","Biography information for Dr Philippa Whitford","Central Ayrshire","Dr Philippa Whitford","4820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751845","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-18","<p>The information requested is not currently available</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-18T09:18:04.453Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751845/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751845/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751845/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-13","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many (a) individuals and (b) households have received Universal Credit and then reverted back to legacy benefits or tax credits.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","4792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751846","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-18","<p>The Real Time Information (RTI) system ensures that we get Universal Credit claims right by providing us with accurate and timely details of earnings and occupational pension payments from Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs’. The HMRC database holding the PAYE data reported in real time (RTI) receives the data from employers, holds it and passes on relevant data for Universal Credit claimants to DWP.</p><p> </p><p>The system is working well with over 99% of individual employment records now being reported in real time. We don’t collect data on the number of claims affected by errors resulting from the real-time information system. However, only a small proportion of the 1% of remaining cases are referred to HMRC to clarify those earnings with the employer</p><p> </p><p>DWP work closely with HMRC to investigate any risks associated with RTI data, and jointly deal with disputes arising when claimants query their reported earnings. As DWP receives copies of the data submitted by employers the risk of data corruption within HMRC is regarded as minimal. However, DWP and HMRC continually monitor the data and no significant problems have been identified.</p><p> </p><p>A number of processes are in place to deal with inaccurate data from employers. DWP and HMRC analysts monitor the RTI data received, looking for trends, patterns and causes. Both Departments then work together with employers and partners such as software developers and payroll bureaux to improve the quality of the data. This work supplements the BACS payment validation process.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","4801","2017-07-18T16:27:18.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751846/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751846/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751846/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-13","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many universal credit claims have been affected by errors resulting from the real-time information system.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","4800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751847","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-18","<p>The Real Time Information (RTI) system ensures that we get Universal Credit claims right by providing us with accurate and timely details of earnings and occupational pension payments from Her Majesty’s Revenue and Customs’. The HMRC database holding the PAYE data reported in real time (RTI) receives the data from employers, holds it and passes on relevant data for Universal Credit claimants to DWP.</p><p> </p><p>The system is working well with over 99% of individual employment records now being reported in real time. We don’t collect data on the number of claims affected by errors resulting from the real-time information system. However, only a small proportion of the 1% of remaining cases are referred to HMRC to clarify those earnings with the employer</p><p> </p><p>DWP work closely with HMRC to investigate any risks associated with RTI data, and jointly deal with disputes arising when claimants query their reported earnings. As DWP receives copies of the data submitted by employers the risk of data corruption within HMRC is regarded as minimal. However, DWP and HMRC continually monitor the data and no significant problems have been identified.</p><p> </p><p>A number of processes are in place to deal with inaccurate data from employers. DWP and HMRC analysts monitor the RTI data received, looking for trends, patterns and causes. Both Departments then work together with employers and partners such as software developers and payroll bureaux to improve the quality of the data. This work supplements the BACS payment validation process.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","4800","2017-07-18T16:27:18.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751847/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751847/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751847/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-13","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the reliability of real-time information for the purposes of calculating universal credit entitlement.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","4801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751848","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-20","<p>Tackling ill health is one of six themes in HSE’s strategy for the health and safety system, ‘Helping Great Britain work well’. The strategy is available at:</p><p><a href="http://www.hse.gov.uk/strategy/index.htm" target="_blank">http://www.hse.gov.uk/strategy/index.htm</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Tackling occupational respiratory disease remains one of HSE’s health priorities and is a key element of HSE’s Health and Work strategy and occupational lung disease plan which are available at:</p><p><a href="http://www.hse.gov.uk/aboutus/strategiesandplans/health-and-work-strategy/index.htm" target="_blank">http://www.hse.gov.uk/aboutus/strategiesandplans/health-and-work-strategy/index.htm</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The aim is to reduce the incidence rate and number of new cases of occupational related lung disease. To help achieve this HSE will focus its inspection and enforcement activity where it can have the most effect and continue to work with a broad range of partners including the recently established Healthy Lung Partnership.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-07-20T15:14:19.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751848/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751848/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751848/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-13","Industrial Diseases: Respiratory System","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps he is taking to reduce the number of people with occupational respiratory disease.","false","Biography information for Peter Aldous","Waveney","Peter Aldous","4817"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751849","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-19","<p>As of the 7th July 2017, 4,589 employers had signed up to Disability Confident.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-07-19T10:13:16.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751849/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751849/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751849/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-13","Employment: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many companies are registered as disability confident.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","4842"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751850","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-20","<p>Travel time by public transport is one of a number of factors that have informed our decisions for all of our future estate, including our preferred location for any new acquisitions. Until we have concluded our commercial arrangements we will not be in a position to provide further details on proposed hub locations, but I can confirm that transport links will be a key consideration.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-20T16:25:57.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751850/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751850/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751850/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-13","Department for Work and Pensions: Treforest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the adequacy of the transport infrastructure from Newport serving the potential site for his Department's hub in Treforest.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","4866"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751851","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-20","<p>Costs associated with the DWP estate are not generally published separately due to commercial sensitivities.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-20T16:29:31.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751851/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751851/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751851/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-13","Department for Work and Pensions: Treforest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will publish the budget for (a) building, (b) designing and (c) purchasing land for his Department's potential new hub in Treforest.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","4865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751852","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-18","<p>DWP have no plans to introduce a 0800 number for the Universal Credit helpline. If a Universal Credit claimant needs to contact us by telephone, they can call the Universal Credit helpline on a 0345 number. Charges for these calls depend on the service provider, but cost no more than a standard geographic call, and count towards any free or inclusive minutes in a caller’s landline or mobile telephone contract. The Department’s guidance directs staff dealing with Universal Credit claims to call customers back either if they request it or if they express any concern about the cost of calling.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-18T09:16:00.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751852/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751852/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751852/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-13","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make the universal credit helpline available free of charge, at least until roll-out is complete.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","4900"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751853","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-18","<p>Universal Credit provides a conversation with all claimants at their initial work search interview to gauge their potential support needs – this could include money advice with a mix of online, telephone and face to face support. If eligible claimants say they are in financial need, an Advance will be made available.</p><p> </p><p>We continue to raise awareness of Advances in different ways, for example, by providing options on the UC Helpline, and signposting this vital support through the new “Universal Credit &amp; You” guide for claimants and the new online Money Manager tool offered by the Money Advice Service.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-18T09:17:35.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751853/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751853/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751853/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-13","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will make it his policy to ensure that everyone making a claim for universal credit is told that they can apply for an advance payment.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","4899"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751854","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-18","<p>Universal Credit have always had a strong working relationship with Citizens Advice colleagues nationally, with particular focus on the exchange of information and emerging issues. The Secretary of State, Universal Credit Director General and I most recently met with the Citizens Advice Chief Executive on 17 July.</p><p> </p><p>At a working level Ministers and UC officials meet regularly with Citizens Advice to share insight. This includes developing a data dashboard to share Citizens Advice Universal Credit claimant contact data with DWP officials.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-18T09:15:34.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751854/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751854/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751854/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-13","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what recent discussions he has had with Citizens Advice about universal credit claimants who (a) face excessive delays in their first payment and periods without any income, (b) find it complex to make and maintain a claim and (c) cannot obtain help when they run into problems; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","4901"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751855","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-18","<p>This Government is clear that zero hours contracts should not be considered as an alternative to proper business planning or used as a permanent arrangement if it is not justifiable. They play a small but important part in the labour market, allowing flexibility for both employers and individuals. People on zero-hour contracts make up less than 3 per cent of the workforce and almost 70 per cent are happy with the number of hours they work, according to the latest ONS Labour Force Survey research (March 2015).</p><p>In May 2015 Government banned the use of exclusivity clauses in zero hours contracts so that people cannot be prevented from looking for or working elsewhere when their employer does not guarantee work.</p><p>Matthew Taylor in his Review of Modern Working Practices has proposed some reforms around zero-hour contracts and Government will consider the whole report carefully and make a full response later this year.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-18T15:16:52.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751855/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751855/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751855/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-13","Zero Hours Contracts","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what safeguards his Department has put in place to protect people employed on zero-hours contracts from exploitation by their employers.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","4889"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751856","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-18","<p>The availability of atypical employment provides a number of benefits for workers who cannot or do not want to commit to ‘standard’ full-time employment. This results in high participation rates among groups which might otherwise be excluded from work altogether, like mothers returning to work.</p><p>The UK’s flexible labour market means those who work in flexible arrangements continue to be entitled to employment protections regardless of the contract type. But we recognise that there are instances where the UK labour market is not working fairly for everyone and is why we asked Matthew Taylor to carry out his independent Review of Working Practices. Our full response later this year will reflect Government’s position and next steps.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-18T15:17:53.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751856/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751856/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751856/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-13","Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what safeguards his Department has put in place to protect people employed on flexible contracts from exploitation by their employers.","false","Biography information for Neil Gray","Airdrie and Shotts","Neil Gray","4890"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751857","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-18","<p>We want employers to create inclusive workplaces which support good mental health, and prevent discriminatory language and practices.</p><p> </p><p>Many employers already have a strong track record in this area and we want to learn from their success, as well as support other employers to create supportive workplace cultures.</p><p> </p><p>There is already a wealth of information available on how employers can support people with mental health conditions. Government sought views on what would further support employers in “Improving Lives - the Work, Health and Disability Green Paper’ and we are now analysing responses to the consultation.</p><p> </p><p>We will also be considering what further guidance could be made available to employers through the internal review of protections from workplace mental health discrimination, announced by the Prime Minister in January.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-07-18T11:16:34.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751857/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751857/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751857/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-13","Employment: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what workplace guidance is available to employers on the use of discriminatory language towards people with a mental illness.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","4940"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751858","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-20","<p>The ‘Reporting of Injuries, Diseases and Dangerous Occurrences Regulations’ (RIDDOR) puts duties on employers, some self-employed and people in control of work premises (the Responsible Person) to report certain serious workplace accidents.</p><p> </p><p>RIDDOR is designed to collect top-level information on such cases, including information on the main accident factor, as assessed by the Responsible person making the report. RIDDOR does not however provide information on contributory factors associated with a reported injury.</p><p> </p><p>Prior to September 2011 injury reports included detailed information on the <strong>main</strong> <strong>agent </strong>causing the injury. The table below shows the number of injuries to workers caused by exposure to hot environmental temperatures as reported to all enforcing authorities under RIDDOR (1995) for the years 2009/10 and 2010/11.</p><p> </p><p><strong>Table</strong>: Injuries to workers caused by exposure to hot environmental temperatures* as reported to all enforcing authorities under RIDDOR (1995), 2009/10 and 2010/11.</p><p>*identified by agent code 16.01: Physical phenom - heat</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>2009/10</p></td><td><p>2010/11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Fatal Injury</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>-</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>-</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Non-fatal injury</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>39</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>42</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Major injury</p></td><td><p>23</p></td><td><p>21</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Over 3-day injury</p></td><td><p>16</p></td><td><p>21</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Since RIDDOR reporting moved online in September 2011 this information is no longer collected, so we cannot identify injuries caused by environmental heat from this date.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-07-20T15:18:28.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751858/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751858/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751858/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-13","Industrial Injuries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many workplace injuries where exposure to high temperatures was a contributory factor were reported to the Health and Safety Executive in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","4921"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751859","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-18","<p>The assessment period and payment structure of Universal Credit creates a fixed period between date of entitlement and the first payment.</p><p> </p><p>The policy intention is that claimants receive the first payment 5 weeks after their date of entitlement (6 weeks if waiting days are served). The assessment period runs for a full calendar month from the date of entitlement, and the UC pay date will be 7 calendar days after the end of the assessment period. This mirrors the world of work and allows for a 1 month period in which to gather information about a claimants’ earnings. Advances and budgeting support are available to support claimants during this period. Advances can provide up to 50% of a claimants indicative award straight away.</p><p> </p><p>The latest internal data, for week ending 19 June, suggests some 80% of cases were paid in full at the end of the first assessment period. For the 20% of cases who were not paid in full we estimate around a third have not signed up to their claimant commitment so cannot be paid until they have. The other two thirds have an outstanding verification issue, such as providing bank statements, evidence of childcare costs, or proof of rent. Many of these claimants receive a part-payment where elements of the claim have been verified.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-18T09:16:33.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751859/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751859/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751859/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-13","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the average time is after an application is submitted for universal credit before the first payment is received.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","4898"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751860","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-20","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","4918","2017-07-20T14:24:46.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751860/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751860/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751860/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-13","Work Capability Assessment: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many appeals have been made to the outcome of work capability assessments in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","4924"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751861","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-07-20","<p>This information is not held centrally.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","4924","2017-07-20T14:24:46.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751861/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751861/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751861/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-07-13","Employment and Support Allowance: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many appeals against decisions on entitlement to employment and support allowance following a work capability assessment were resolved within (a) three, (b) three to six, (c) six to nine, (d) nine to 12 and (e) over 12 months in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sir David Crausby","Bolton North East","Sir David Crausby","4918"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751862","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-21","<p>Costs associated with the DWP estate are not generally published separately due to commercial sensitivities.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-21T12:58:58.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751862/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751862/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751862/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-13","Department for Work and Pensions: Treforest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the budget is for (a) building, (b) design and (c) cost of the land of his Department's proposed Pensions Hub in Treforest.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","4954"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751863","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-18","<p>As a large employer, DWP understands the potential impact that a closure or relocation of an office may have. This is why we carefully considered the wider impacts on local communities, like Merthyr Tydfil, as part of the review of our estate.</p><p> </p><p>It is important to remember that the economic impact of employment is dispersed beyond the specific location of a workplace and staff currently based at Merthyr Tidfil already live in the broader area around the site. While we expect the majority of these staff to be relocated to a new place of work, it is unlikely that a significant proportion of them will also move their place of residence.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-18T09:18:56.313Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751863/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751863/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751863/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-13","Department for Work and Pensions: Location","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect on the local economy of towns such as Merthyr Tydfil as a result of the proposed relocation of his Department's offices.","false","Biography information for Gerald Jones","Merthyr Tydfil and Rhymney","Gerald Jones","4985"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751864","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-18","<p>Under the Public Sector Equality Duty the Department is required to consider the potential impact on people with protected characteristics when making policy decisions and delivering services. We have therefore carried out equality analyses wherever our plans are to close or co-locate an office or service. We used the findings to understand the potential impact of changes to our estate on people – both for the Department’s employees and people using our services.</p><p> </p><p>During the consultation process with individual employees who are required to move, their future journey in the context of a working day and relevant personal circumstances, such as caring responsibilities, form part of the decision making process as to whether they will move or the Department will seek to redeploy them into an alternative role.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-18T09:18:32.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751864/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751864/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751864/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-13","Department for Work and Pensions: Location","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what impact assessment he has made of the effect of the proposed relocation on the quality of life for his Department's staff who will be relocated, particularly in relation to (a) the increase in the length of their working day due to travel time and (b) the effect on those with caring responsibilities.","false","Biography information for Gerald Jones","Merthyr Tydfil and Rhymney","Gerald Jones","4970"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751865","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-18","<p>I am replying to both questions as assessments of the effect of the benefit cap are the responsibility of the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The new, lower, tiered benefit cap was introduced from 7 November 2016. The change reduces the total amount a working-age household can receive in benefits to £20,000 for couples and lone parents (£13,400 for single adults with no children) in Great Britain outside Greater London. Within Greater London the level is £23,000 for couples and lone parents (£15,410 for single adults with no children).</p><p>Evidence from the 2014 evaluation of the cap showed very little, if any, impact on homelessness as a direct result of the cap. In the cases of a small numbers of capped households who had been evicted, the Local Authorities noted that they had other reasons for rent arrears and they also failed to engage with relevant services, they were considered intentionally homeless.</p><p> </p><p>The lower cap is still the equivalent of gross family earnings of £25k, and £29k in London. There are a number of exemptions, for example, for people receiving disability payments or people who work and qualify for Working Tax Credits. Discretionary Housing Payments can be made by local authorities to help people adjust to the benefit cap and those payments can be made to prevent people becoming homeless.</p><p> </p><p>To help Local Authorities protect the most vulnerable and to support households adjusting to the reforms, the Government has provided around £900 million funding for the Discretionary Housing Payments scheme since 2011.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","4986","2017-07-18T14:29:26.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751865/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751865/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751865/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-13","Social Security Benefits: Homelessness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect of the proposed reduction in the benefit cap to £23,000 per year on the level of homelessness.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","4987"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751866","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-07-18","<p>DWP has been mindful of its duties under the Equality Act 2010 and has carried out local level equality analysis to inform understanding of the effect of our plans. Careful consideration has been given to the wider effect on the local communities. DWP will maintain services to claimants, whether in their existing jobcentre where a decision is made to retain that office or, where their existing jobcentre will close, at an alternative site. DWP will consider any requests for equality analysis reports in the normal course of business.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s responses to public consultations for some jobcentres are published on Gov.uk at the following address:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?keywords=&amp;publication_filter_option=consultations&amp;topics%5B%5D=all&amp;departments%5B%5D=department-for-work-pensions&amp;official_document_status=all&amp;world_locations%5B%5D=all&amp;from_date=&amp;to_date" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications?keywords=&amp;publication_filter_option=consultations&amp;topics%5B%5D=all&amp;departments%5B%5D=department-for-work-pensions&amp;official_document_status=all&amp;world_locations%5B%5D=all&amp;from_date=&amp;to_date</a>=</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-07-18T09:19:44.92Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751866/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751866/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751866/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-07-13","Department for Work and Pensions: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he plans to publish his Department's equality impact assessment for his Department's estates consultation.","false","Biography information for Jessica Morden","Newport East","Jessica Morden","4971"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751867","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-19","<p>The Department doesn’t collect data on the number of small and microbusinesses who have switched supplier.</p><p>It is important that small and microbusinesses are aware of their ability to switch and engage in the energy market. The Government therefore supports the Competition Markets Authority’s remedies which Ofgem have implemented to help these customers access better energy deals.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-19T13:54:29.583Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751867/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751867/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751867/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-13","Energy: Business","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 12 July 2017 to Question 3324, on energy: small businesses, how many businesses have switched energy suppliers; and what steps he has taken to raise awareness among businesses of the availability of different tariffs.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","4949"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751868","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-19","<p>Under the Reporting on Payment Practices and Performance Regulations 2017, a named company Director, or designated member in the case of LLPs, must approve the information being provided, taking responsibility for its accuracy. It is a criminal offence to knowingly or recklessly publish information that is false or misleading. The Government will investigate any challenges to the accuracy of the information provided, on a case by case basis. Anyone who is concerned that a business might not have complied, or may have made a false statement, can raise this by contacting the company directly or by contacting the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy at <a href="mailto:paymentpracticesreporting@beis.gov.uk" target="_blank">paymentpracticesreporting@beis.gov.uk</a>.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-19T13:54:14.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751868/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751868/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751868/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-13","Business: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 12 July 2017 to Question 3326, what steps he plans to take to ensure accurate reporting by large businesses on their payment practices.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","4948"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751869","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-19","<p>Some of the reforms recommended by the Competition Markets Authority’s investigation, such as increasing price transparency for smaller microbusinesses and improving prompts to engage should make a real difference to the way the market works.</p><p>Ofgem has announced plans to consult on further measures to help microbusinesses.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-19T10:58:48.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751869/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751869/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751869/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-13","Energy: Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 12 July 2017 to Question 3324, on energy: small businesses, what assessment he has made of the potential merits of the proposal by the Competition and Markets Authority to help microbusinesses access better energy deals.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","4950"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751870","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-19","<p>The franchising and partnership powers in the Act commenced on 27th June 2017, and it is up to local authorities to put these powers into practice. However, the Government understands, through local engagement, that a number of local authorities are actively engaging with bus operators to determine how best to improve bus services. The Government is not party to local conversations between authorities, bus operators and local businesses.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2017-07-19T10:56:19.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751870/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751870/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751870/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-13","Business: Public Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 11 July 2017 to Question 3183, which local authorities are using the powers in the Bus Services Act 2017 to work with businesses.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","4951"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751871","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-19","<p>The Start Up Loans Scheme was launched in 2012 as a response to Lord Young’s report into small business and enterprise ‘Make Business Your Business’. This is therefore the date from which figures are held.</p><p>I can confirm that since 2012, in the North West, a total of 5,563 start-up loans have been delivered, equalling £35.64m.</p><p>And, in the UK, since 2012, a total of 46,506 loans have been granted, to a sum of £301.37m.</p><p>The attached table shows by year the number and value of start-up loans.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-19T10:59:45.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751871/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751871/answer","start-up-loans.pdf","start-up-loans.pdf","Start Up Loans stats","Start Up Loans stats","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751871/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-13","Self-employed: Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, pursuant to the Answer of 10 July 2017 to Question 3182, what estimate he has made of the number of start-up loans paid to people who are self-employed in (a) North West England and (b) the UK in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Bill Esterson","Sefton Central","Bill Esterson","4994"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751872","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-18","<p>I made an oral statement to the House on 11 July 2017 to announce the publication of the Matthew Taylor Review of Modern Working Practices.</p><p> </p><p>The report is comprehensive and detailed and, as Matthew Taylor himself recognises, is just the start of a long term programme. It will require detailed, careful thought and further consultation. It is important that we take action where we need to. So we will spend the next few months building on the debate that Matthew has created and engage with stakeholders to discuss the report. We need to listen to what those who engaged in this review feel about it.</p><p> </p><p>This Government will give the report the careful consideration it deserves and will respond in full later this year.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-18T13:41:51.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751872/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751872/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751872/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-13","Modern Working Practices Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when the Government plans to respond to each of the recommendations made by the Taylor Review of Modern Employment Practices.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","4861"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751873","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-18","<p>The objective of Government’s Industrial Strategy is to increase productivity and drive growth across the United Kingdom. We have provided a framework to build on the strengths of different places and address the factors that hold others back. This will include investing in key infrastructure projects, increasing skill levels, and backing local innovation strengths.</p><p>In the North East the Industrial Strategy will build on the £379.6m million Local Growth Fund awarded to the North East LEP, which will bring an estimated 8,200 jobs and up to £300 million of public and private sector matched investment to the area.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-18T15:10:01.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751873/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751873/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751873/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-13","Productivity: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps the Government is taking to address the regional productivity gap in the North East.","false","Biography information for Mr Stephen Hepburn","Jarrow","Mr Stephen Hepburn","4846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751874","Department for Education","false","2017-07-21","<p>There have been 71,290 apprenticeship starts recorded to date (August 2016 to April 2017) in the North West in the 2016 to 2017 academic year.</p><p> </p><p>Earlier years’ data for starts by region can be found in the apprenticeships FE data library:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/586183/apprenticeships-starts-by-geography-learner-demographics-and-sector-subject-area.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/586183/apprenticeships-starts-by-geography-learner-demographics-and-sector-subject-area.xlsx</a></p><p> </p><p>Data for apprenticeship participation by region is also available in the apprenticeships FE data library:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/624357/apprenticeships-participation-by-region-and-sector-subject-area.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/624357/apprenticeships-participation-by-region-and-sector-subject-area.xlsx</a></p><p> </p><p>More detailed geographical data on apprenticeship starts and achievements are available in the apprenticeships FE data library tools:</p><p> </p><p>Starts: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/624428/apprenticeships-geography-data-tool-starts-v1.xlsm" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/624428/apprenticeships-geography-data-tool-starts-v1.xlsm</a></p><p> </p><p>Achievements: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/624585/apprenticeships-geography-data-tool-achievements-v1.xlsm" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/624585/apprenticeships-geography-data-tool-achievements-v1.xlsm</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong><br> </strong></p><p> </p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-07-21T11:25:47.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751874/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751874/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751874/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-07-13","Apprentices: North West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what progress the Government has made on increasing the number of apprenticeships in the North West.","false","Biography information for Trudy Harrison","Copeland","Trudy Harrison","4833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751875","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-21","<p>The table shows average (mean) annual electricity consumption per domestic meter in the UK, split by country since 2010.</p><p><strong>Average UK annual domestic electricity consumption (kWh), 2010-15</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>2010</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>England</strong></p></td><td><p>4,163</p></td><td><p>4,095</p></td><td><p>4,035</p></td><td><p>3,963</p></td><td><p>3,972</p></td><td><p>3,914</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Wales</strong></p></td><td><p>3,916</p></td><td><p>3,845</p></td><td><p>3,787</p></td><td><p>3,736</p></td><td><p>3,734</p></td><td><p>3,685</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Scotland</strong></p></td><td><p>4,148</p></td><td><p>4,059</p></td><td><p>3,969</p></td><td><p>3,852</p></td><td><p>3,918</p></td><td><p>3,836</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Northern Ireland</strong></p></td><td><p>3,956</p></td><td><p>3,744</p></td><td><p>3,915</p></td><td><p>3,998</p></td><td><p>3,775</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>UK</strong></p></td><td><p>4,146</p></td><td><p>4,074</p></td><td><p>4,014</p></td><td><p>3,941</p></td><td><p>3,952</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Figures for Northern Ireland were taken from BEIS’ sub-national domestic electricity consumption statistics in Northern Ireland:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/experimental-sub-national-domestic-electricity-consumption-statistics-for-northern-ireland-2009" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/experimental-sub-national-domestic-electricity-consumption-statistics-for-northern-ireland-2009</a></p><p>All other figures were taken from BEIS’ sub-national electricity consumption statistics:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/sub-national-electricity-consumption-data" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/sub-national-electricity-consumption-data</a></p><p>Consumption data for Northern Ireland for 2015 will be published in September 2017, with GB data for 2016 published in December 2017.</p><p>These figures show consumption per electricity meter rather than per household. These differ slightly as some households have more than one electricity meter while others have less (due to sharing a meter with neighbouring households). Figures on a household basis are available for Great Britain via the second link above, but are unavailable for Northern Ireland or the UK as a whole.</p><p>Figures for the UK include consumption for households which couldn’t be assigned to a particular country due to incomplete address data.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-07-21T12:51:25.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751875/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751875/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751875/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-13","Electricity: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what the annual average household electricity consumption was in (a) the UK, (b) England, (c) Scotland, (d) Wales and (e) Northern Ireland since 2010.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","4835"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751876","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-18","<p>The most recent UK wide forecasts of the number of employers paying the levy in different sectors are published by the Department for Education, and can be found online at:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/545145/Apprenticeships_-expected_levy_and_total_spend_-_Aug_2016.pdf.</p><p> </p><p>A more detailed sector breakdown, splitting out shipping and offshore energy industries from the published categories, is not available.</p><p> </p><p>The Apprenticeship Levy applies to all employers operating across all sectors. An allowance of £15,000 means only those with a pay bill exceeding £3 million have to pay the levy. Therefore companies in the shipping and offshore energy industries are liable to pay the Apprenticeship Levy only if they have a pay bill of over £3 million.</p><p>Guidance on what counts towards the paybill can be found online at: https://www.gov.uk/guidance/pay-apprenticeship-levy</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-07-18T14:51:57.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751876/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751876/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751876/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-13","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many employers in the (a) shipping and (b) offshore energy industries are liable to pay the Apprenticeship Levy; and for what reasons companies in those industries are not liable to pay the Levy.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","4779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751877","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-18","<p>In collaboration with the Department for Transport and maritime stakeholders, we have been developing more detailed guidance on minimum wage law with respect to seafarers. Once this work has been completed, the guidance relating to seafarers will be published as part of a periodic update to the broader guidance on compliance with the National Minimum Wage.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-18T13:13:15.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751877/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751877/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751877/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-13","Merchant Shipping: Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when he plans to update his Department's guidance on National Minimum Wage Enforcement for seafarers.","false","Biography information for Karl Turner","Kingston upon Hull East","Karl Turner","4780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751878","Department for International Trade","false","2017-07-18","<p>The UK has long supported the promotion of our values globally and this will continue as we leave the EU. We do not shy away from confronting barriers to trade and investment – including issues of human rights and corruption.</p><p>The Department for International Trade is working closely with other departments in particular the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO). Ministerial Briefing for every country visited includes country profiles provided by the FCO which where appropriate, set out human rights issues.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-07-18T16:33:31.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751878/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751878/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751878/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-07-13","Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, if he will list the human rights priority countries that he or Ministers in his Department have visited over the last 12 months; what briefings on human rights such Ministers received before those visits; and what discussions those Ministers had on human rights in each of those visits.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","4965"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751879","Department for International Trade","false","2017-07-18","<p>The UK is strongly committed to the protection and promotion of human rights worldwide. The National Action Plan on Business and Human Rights is included in the Department for International Trade’s online advice to businesses operating in Saudi Arabia to highlight the UN Guiding Principles on Business and Human Rights and their responsibilities under national and international law wherever they operate. In addition, the Department continues to work with all international partners on the promotion of Human Rights in its international engagements.</p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2017-07-18T16:32:19.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751879/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751879/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751879/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-07-13","Overseas Trade: Saudi Arabia","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, how the National Action Plan on Business and Human Rights has informed his Department's policies on trade and investment with Saudi Arabia.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","4966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751880","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-18","<p>The UK was the first state to publish a National Action Plan to implement the United Nations Guiding Principles on Business and Human Rights. This Plan brings together a range of measures – national and international, mandatory and voluntary – to foster business respect for human rights. These include the world leading provision in the Modern Slavery Act 2015, which requires large companies to say what they do to ensure modern slavery is not taking place in their business or through their supply chains, support for the Corporate Human Rights Benchmark, a business-led initiative to rank the world’s largest businesses on their approach to human rights and continuing encouragement to other countries to produce their own National Action Plans.</p><p>The Joint Committee on Human Rights’ recent inquiry on human rights and business which culminated in its report “Human Rights and Business 2017: Promoting responsibility and ensuring accountability” examined human rights and business in the UK including the implementation of the UK’s National Action Plan. The Government will respond to the report when the Committee reconvenes after summer recess.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-18T15:18:51.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751880/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751880/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751880/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-13","Business: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the effect of the National Action Plan on Business and Human Rights on (a) business practices and (b) international efforts to uphold human rights.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","4967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751881","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-07-18","<p>My right hon. Friend the Secretary of State is committed to the Government’s approach on business and human rights and the Department jointly leads with the Foreign and Commonwealth Office on the UK’s National Action Plan. Together we drive cross-Government delivery of its commitments through an official-level steering group.</p><p>Ministers and officials from this Department and across Government have discussions in many contexts with business and civil society organisations, which touch on aspects of the very broad business and human rights agenda, for example, on such matters as labour practices, equality and diversity, health and safety, modern slavery, and more besides.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-07-18T15:19:43.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751881/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751881/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751881/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-07-13","Business: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with (a) his Cabinet colleagues, (b) business leaders and (c) civil society organisations on the Government's National Action Plan on Business and Human Rights.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","4968"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751882","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-21","<p>As set out in the policy paper “Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU,” our first priority is to reach agreement on the post-exit position of EU citizens now living in the UK and of UK nationals living in other EU countries. Our aim is to ensure that EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU can broadly live their lives as they do now. We will discuss in negotiations with the EU how to ensure that UK nationals in the EU will be able to rely on the rights agreed, just as EU nationals will be able to rely on those rights in the UK legal system.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-07-21T10:34:45.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751882/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751882/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751882/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-13","Immigration: British Nationals Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, with reference to the Government's publication Safeguarding the Position of EU Citizens Living in the UK and UK Nationals Living in the EU, published on 26 June 2017, what steps he plans to take during negotiations of the UK leaving the EU to ensure that the UK retains a role in maintaining the rights of UK nationals in the EU.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","4955"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751883","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-19","<p>DExEU Ministers and officials have held roundtables, visits, and bilateral meetings with organisations including youth groups, faith groups, and charity bodies. Details of Ministerial meetings will be published in the Department's Quarterly Transparency Returns, which will be made publicly available on GOV.UK.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-07-19T10:26:50.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751883/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751883/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751883/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-13","Equality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 4 July 2017 to Question 2771, if he will publish a list of the groups and organisations his Department is engaging with in order to represent the diverse communities of the UK throughout its negotiation process.","false","Biography information for Dawn Butler","Brent Central","Dawn Butler","4939"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751884","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-07-18","<p>The exact reciprocal agreements will be reached through negotiations with our European partners. We are both clear that we want to protect the broad range of rights and entitlements currently enjoyed by both EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU. We want to seek a reciprocal agreement with the EU to safeguard the rights of UK citizens, but it will be for the EU and its Member States to decide how they will implement any agreed deal.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-07-18T11:16:37.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751884/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751884/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751884/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-07-13","Immigration: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 7 July 2017 to Question 1733, whether the exact reciprocal agreements to be reached through negotiations with European partners may differ from the position set out by the Government in its recent publication of 26 June 2017, Safeguarding the position of EU citizens in the UK and UK nationals in the EU.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","4775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751885","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-20","<p>The government is committed to intensive engagement with the devolved administrations on all areas of EU exit, including common frameworks. The First Secretary of State has written to the First Minister of Wales, Deputy First Minister of Scotland and senior officials have has written to the interim Head of the Civil Service in the Northern Ireland Executive Office, to instigate this process. Discussions will seek to build an understanding of areas that will and will not require a common framework. Both Ministerial and official meetings will take place during the summer.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-07-20T15:08:43.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751885/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751885/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751885/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-13","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the format will be for the intensive discussions with devolved administrations on common frameworks referred to in his letter to hon. Members.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","4871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751955","Cabinet Office","false","2017-07-19","<p>We recognise the need to ensure government research is available and can be easily accessed.</p><p>Departments can already publish research in a single place, the<a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank"> GOV.UK </a> website, and we are constantly improving this website to make it easier for users to find the information they need.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-07-19T16:10:17.15Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751955/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751955/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751955/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-13",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what action they are taking to establish a register of research commissioned by Government departments.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL790"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751956","Cabinet Office","false","2017-09-14","<p>There are currently no such plans.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-09-14T15:47:14.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751956/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751956/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751956/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-07-13",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government whether they have any plans to commemorate in October the many millions who have died, since the October Revolution 1917, as a result of the actions of the governments of the USSR, the National Socialist government of Germany, the Communist Party of China, the Democratic Republic of Kampuchea, the Democratic People's Republic of Korea, the Democratic Republic of Vietnam, the People's Democratic Republic of Ethiopia, the People's Republic of Bulgaria, the German Democratic Republic, the Republic of Cuba, the People's Republic of Angola, the People's Socialist Republic of Albania, the Lao People's Democratic Republic, the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela and other countries which established governments founded on Marxist-socialist principles.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751957","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-07-27","<p>The overall information on grant-in-aid funding to the BBC World Service is available to Parliament through the Supplementary Estimates, however the information for each service is not available. The Supplementary Estimates should be available online for a large part of the period in question but the Parliamentary library should hold the information for the whole period in question.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-07-27T13:34:10.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751957/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751957/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751957/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-07-13",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what level of grant-in-aid funding was provided to each service within the BBC World Service in each of the financial years 1987–88 to 2014–15; and, for each service, how much of that funding was allocated to (1) operating grants-in-aid, and (2) capital grants.","false","Biography information for Lord Suri",,"Lord Suri","HL792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751958","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-19","<p>The Government’s Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy was published in April 2017, and sets out our plans to increase cycling and walking across England. The strategy aims to make cycling and walking the natural choices for short journeys or as part of a longer journey, and identifies £1.2 billion which may be invested in support of this over the five years from 2016/17 to 2020/21. Alongside the Strategy, the Government published guidance for local authorities to help them develop their own local Cycling and Walking Infrastructure Plans, and will be providing further support to local authorities to help them develop these plans.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-07-19T13:41:27.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751958/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751958/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751958/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-13",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what action they are taking to increase the number of cyclists outside London.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL793"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751959","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-24","<p>Electrification to Cardiff is scheduled for completion in December 2018.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-07-24T10:45:00.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751959/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751959/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751959/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-13",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what progress is being made to electrify the rail lines to South Wales.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751960","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-20","<p>The Government’s investment in track and signalling infrastructure as part of the Great North Rail Project, and additional train services to be delivered through the new Northern franchise, will bring significant benefits to Bradford by providing more and faster services with new connections to Manchester, Manchester Airport, Liverpool, Warrington, Chester, Sheffield and Nottingham by the end of 2019 - all operated with brand new trains. Furthermore, additional direct trains to London are planned by the Virgin Trains East Coast franchise.</p><p> </p><p>Bradford is also benefiting from locally-sponsored investment in the rail network including the opening of two new stations at Low Moor and Apperley Bridge.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport is working closely with Transport for the North to assess the case for Northern Powerhouse Rail (NPR) including whether the NPR network can serve key markets such as Bradford.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-07-20T10:41:52.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751960/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751960/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751960/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-13",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what action they are taking to improve the rail network around Bradford.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751961","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-24","<p>The Department for Transport, through the Action Plan for Information on Rail Fares and Ticketing Information, is working with industry and other stakeholders to make it easier for passengers to choose the right fares for them. An interim report on delivery against this plan will be published in the forthcoming Office of Rail and Road (ORR) Annual Consumer Report.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-07-24T10:48:31.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751961/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751961/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751961/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-13",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what action they are taking to simplify rail ticketing for the benefit of passengers.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751962","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-24","<p>Virgin Trains East Coast (VTEC) is fulfilling its obligations to both the government and passengers alike. VTEC is delivering real passenger improvements, including refurbishing their current fleet, increasing service frequency and introducing new destinations. VTEC operate 15% more services today than in 2016.</p><p><br>Passenger satisfaction is increasing - VTEC topped the independent National Rail Passenger Survey in Autumn 2017 for long distance operators, at 91% satisfaction.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-07-24T10:49:25.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751962/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751962/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751962/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-13",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the operation of the East Coast Main Line since the award of the new contract in 2014.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751963","Department for Transport","false","2017-07-24","<p>Network Rail published an update to its Enhancement Delivery Plan on 30 June 2017. This sets out the outputs, scope and milestones for the projects, including electrification schemes, which Network Rail is committed to deliver. Each project entry includes a milestones table setting out the programme for a project’s delivery.</p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2017-07-24T10:57:09.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751963/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751963/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751963/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-07-13",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government what projects to electrify rail lines in England are currently subject to delays in (1) commencement, and (2) completion, of works.","false","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751964","Department of Health","false","2017-07-19","<p>The Health Premium Incentive Scheme was a pilot exercise carried out in 2014/15. The Government currently has no plans to implement a similar scheme.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-07-19T15:06:37.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751964/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751964/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751964/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-07-13",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government whether they have abandoned the Health Premium approach to funding part of the public health responsibilities of local government; and if so, why.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL799"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751965","HM Treasury","false","2017-07-24","<p>The government has no current plans to review the decision not to introduce a tobacco levy. A levy would complicate the tax system, impose an administrative burden on businesses and HMRC and would create uncertainty for businesses and consumers.</p><p> </p><p>The government remains committed to its objectives on tobacco policy; to raise revenue and protect public health. Budget 2017 increased tobacco duty rates by 2% above RPI inflation. In addition, a Minimum Excise Tax of £5.37 on a pack of 20 cigarettes was introduced on 20 May 2017, alongside standardised packaging and the new Tobacco Products Directive.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-07-24T14:29:21.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751965/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751965/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751965/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-07-13",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government, in the light of the decision to introduce the Soft Drinks Industry Levy, whether they will review their decision in 2015 not to impose a levy on tobacco products; and if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751966","Home Office","true","2017-07-20","<p>Asylum seekers who would otherwise be destitute can apply for free accommodation and cash support to cover their essential living needs whilst their cases are considered.</p><p>If they have an emergency need for accommodation they can ask to be put in initial accommodation whilst their support applications are being processed and the vast majority of such requests are processed on the same day. We aim to resolve Section 95 applications received from people in Initial Accommodation within 3 days and other applications from people staying in private accommodation within 10 days. All cases are considered on their own merits, in some cases applicants are asked to provide further information before a decision on eligibility can reached. Information on the average length of time between asylum support application and payment is not routinely collected and could only be provided by examination of individual case records, which would result in disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-07-20T10:44:01.78Z","2017-07-20T14:36:50.94Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751966/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751966/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751966/answer",,"Lord Lee of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/751966/answer/previousversion/6009",,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-07-13",,"2","House of Lords","Her Majesty's Government to what timescale they aim to issue decisions on applications from asylum seekers for section 95 accommodation and subsistence support.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL801"
